{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622151"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:01:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:01:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16789"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16789"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.05,0.48,0.19,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76699"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9480"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16789"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62191"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5236"},{"type":"tags","id":"5238"},{"type":"tags","id":"7614"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22411"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22628"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76699"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAnthracycline antibiotics are important chemotherapeutic agents used in the treatment of various cancers including breast cancer, lymphoma, and sarcoma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of anthracycline chemotherapy drugs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits dihydrofolate reductase","Blocks epidermal growth factor receptors","Intercalates into DNA and inhibits topoisomerase II","Alkylates DNA bases directly","Binds tubulin and prevents microtubule formation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAnthracyclines like doxorubicin primarily work by two mechanisms, \u003Cstrong\u003Eintercalating into DNA and inhibiting topoisomerase II\u003C/strong\u003E. Intercalation into DNA prevents the transcription and translation of DNA and cell division. The inhibition of topoisomerase II leads to eventual apoptosis. They also generate free radicals which contribute to both their anti-cancer effects and one of their major side effects, cardiotoxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of dihydrofolate reductase\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of action of methotrexate, which interferes with folate metabolism and DNA synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETargeted therapies such as erlotinib, which inhibit cell growth signalling pathways, work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking epidermal growth factor receptors\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlkylates DNA bases directly\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of alkylating agents such as cyclophosphamide, which form cross-links in DNA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinds tubulin and prevents microtubule formation\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of vinca alkaloids such as vincristine, which disrupt cell division.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the mechanism of anthracyclines is important as it explains both their effectiveness against rapidly dividing cancer cells and their potential for causing cardiotoxicity through free radical generation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anthracyclines work by intercalating into DNA and inhibiting topoisomerase II, leading to DNA damage and cell death.","Doxorubicin is a common anthracycline chemotherapy drug used to treat many cancers.","Cardiotoxicity is a major dose-limiting side effect of anthracycline therapy due to free radical generation."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Shandilya M, Sharma S, Prasad Das P, Charak S. Molecular-Level Understanding of the Anticancer Action Mechanism of Anthracyclines [Internet]. Advances in Precision Medicine Oncology. IntechOpen; 2021. Available from: http://dx.doi.org/10.5772/intechopen.94180"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62191"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16789"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62191"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T10:55:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T10:56:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9480"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76699"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"re